entry.content:
We cannot create fallback textures on ChromeOS as the media client

requests creation with external sampler. This happens currently when

GpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool creates buffer with SharedMemory and

requests compound image backing. With Compound backing, we cannot

have external textures, so it goes through fallback creation which

crashes due to texture target mismatch and would have failed fallback

creation gracefully earlier with GrTextureType::kExternal match.

This change allows also checking for PrefersExternalSampler so that

it returns properly.



Ideally, we should add support for creating compound shared image with

shared memory GMBs with P010 format by checking the proper capability

in media which checks for format and texture target support.

entry.title: Allow cross-origin subframes to send automatic beacons.
entry.content:
Fenced frames can send out reporting beacons if an event occurs.

However, only same-origin documents are allowed to send automatic

beacons. This restriction is problematic when a subframe from a

third-party ad server is embedded in an ad loaded with a script from

that server. One such use case is when an ad frame embeds a subframe

that loads the actual contents of an ad. This is known as Third-party ad

serving, or 3PAS.



The solution to allow cross-origin subframes to send automatic beacons

involves four parts: subframes will opt in through a header, the main ad

frame will opt in to allow cross-origin subframes to use its automatic

beacon data when sending automatic beacons, the subframe will then be

able to use the automatic beacon data that is stored in its frame tree's

FencedFrameConfig, and the automatic beacon data will be stored

per-document rather than per-fenced frame config.



The opt-in mechanism for the main ad frame's data is a new

"crossOriginExposed" parameter in

`setReportEventDataForAutomaticBeacons()`, which defaults to false.



The opt-in mechanism for the cross-origin subframe is done through a new

"Allow-Fenced-Frame-Automatic-Beacons" response header.



The reason for storing the beacon data per-document is a security one.

With the current setup, a same-origin subframe of an ad frame could set

automatic beacon data, and a different cross-origin subframe could then

use that data. Since those two frames are not direct descendants of each

other, we want to prevent that behavior, and instead only allow

documents to use opted in data set by direct ancestors.



This CL also modifies the automatic beacon web platform tests to

properly handle multiple beacons being sent with the same data. The

automatic beacon store endpoint now accepts a "beacon type" parameter

that is added to the hash when storing/retrieving a beacon. This will

prevent collisions if two beacons with different types are sent with

the same data.

entry.title: Rename {absl => std}::optional in //chromeos/
entry.content:
Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^chromeos" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""

git cl format

```



Note: I added the `IncludeBlocks: Regroup` option to clang-format

entry.title: Add a synthetic trial for limited entropy randomization.
entry.content:
The synthetic trial selects 50% of clients to be eligible for a limited entropy field trial. The trial will not be registered unless explicitly registered (thru `VariationsServiceClient::RegisterLimitedEntropySyntheticTrial`). This change only contains the synthetic trial setup, and does not contain the registration logic.



The trial is represented by `variations::LimitedEntropySyntheticTrial`. `variations::VariationsService` will own and construct this object. Follow-up CLs will add logic to determine when the trial will be registered.



Browser tests are not added as part of this CL since the trial is not registered. I will add browser tests once the registration logic is completed.



Low-Coverage-Reason: TESTS_IN_SEPARATE_CL. `VariationsServiceClient::RegisterLimitedEntropySyntheticTrial` is not used for now and tests will be added in follow-up CLs when it's being called.

entry.title: TaskAttribution: Refactor ancestor checking
entry.content:
Simplify TaskAttributionTracker::IsAncestor and related methods:

- Remove TaskAttributionTracker::AncestorStatus enum. kUnknown is no

longer used, and returning bool in in Is* method is simpler.



- Make IsAncestor() take a task instead of a ScriptState. The

script state was needed for an internal call to RunningTask, which

is needed because the API assumes the running task. Instead, pass

the task, which is more flexible. This allows removing ScriptState

from this and GetAncestorFromSet, which simplifies the move to

per-Isolate continuation data.



- Replace GetAncestorFromSet with the more generic ForEachAncestor,

which takes a root task and a visitor function. IsAncestor is now

implemented with this, and the one consumer of GetAncestorFromSet

was updated to pass a lambda. This similifies the implementation and

is more flexible (e.g. it doesn't require a certain data structure

for the set).

entry.title: Update printing browser tests for system print API variations
entry.content:
The XPS print pipeline for Windows has significant differences compared

to how a print document is handled when printing using GDI. Prepare

for tests to be able to cover both cases by including a platform print

API variation for the test suite parameters.



Note that this CL is a mechanical change in that it does not cause new

tests to be run for XPS. The same number and type of tests which ran

previously still run with this change. Follow-on changes will include

the XPS variations to increase test coverage.



Since XPS platform calls are not allowed from the browser process,

use of testing::Combine() is avoided for automatically generating the

new platform print API testing combinations. A local helper method to

generate valid combinations is used instead.



Apply a naming convention for the generation of strings used for test

suffixes. Functions which take a testing::TestParamInfo<> parameter

are generating the complete suffix, and thus have names which end with

"TestSuffix()". Other functions that take variation parameters are

helpers for making the test suffix, and thus have names that just end

with "String()".



For platforms other than Windows, a current placeholder of platform

print API is identified as CUPS. This generally matches the API used

by the other desktop platforms for which these tests are run. That is,

no distinction is made for whether IPP is used for CUPS.

entry.title: Support redundant response start in PageTimingMetricsSender.
entry.content:
PageTimingMetricsSender::DidStartResponse() can be invoked multiple

times with the same resource id, despite the long-standing DCHECK

suggesting that it doesn't happen (see bug for repro). Prior to

crrev.com/c/4321469, when that happened, the `PageResourceDataUse`

instance already in `page_resource_data_use_` was reused (emplace()

no-ops if the element already exist). Since crrev.com/c/4321469,

the existing `PageResourceDataUse` was deleted and replaced with

a new one. This could result in a dangling pointer in

`modified_resources_`. This CL solves the issue by making

`InsertPageResourceDataUse()` no-op if there is already an entry

with the given id in `page_resource_data_use_`.
